bug.short_desc: GCC 7 miscompiles Clang 4.0 in when CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release
bug.cf_doc_type: If docs needed, set a value

long_desc.thetext:
Description of problem: Clang 4.0 compiled with GCC 6 works fine, while when compiled with GCC 7 fails to pass some of the tests.
Version-Release number of selected component (if applicable): $ gcc --version gcc (GCC) 7.0.1 20170225 (Red Hat 7.0.1-0.10) $ gcc --version gcc (GCC) 7.0.1 20170225 (Red Hat 7.0.1-0.10)
How reproducible: Every time.
Steps to Reproduce: 1. git clone https://github.com/llvm-mirror/llvm.git 2. cd llvm/tools 3. git clone https://github.com/llvm-mirror/clang.git 4. cd .. 5. git checkout release_40; git -C tools/clang release_40
Now we got LLVM and Clang, time to build.
6. mkdir build 7. cd build 8. cmake -DBUILD_SHARED_LIBS=ON -DLLVM_LIBDIR_SUFFIX=64 .. 9. make -j4; make -j4 check-all
Observe all tests running successfully.
10. mkdir build-release 11. cd build-release 12. cmake -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release -DBUILD_SHARED_LIBS=ON -DLLVM_LIBDIR_SUFFIX=64 .. 13. make -j4; make -j4 check-all
Obseve some test failing; I will attach ltrace output of a particular test.

Created attachment 1259195 ltrace clang-format disable-include-sorting.cpp [release, compiled with GCC 6]

Created attachment 1259199 ltrace clang-format disable-include-sorting.cpp [release, compiled with GCC 7]

Might as well be just undefined behavior in LLVM/Clang. Does: -fno-strict-aliasing -fwrapv -fno-aggressive-loop-optimizations -fno-lifetime-dse make a difference? Can you try -fsanitize=undefined and/or -fsanitize=address ? If you build with -O0 instead of the default (-O2/-O3 or whatever it uses), do you still observe issues? If not, can you bisect which LLVM/Clang *.o file matters for the test failure?

(In reply to Jakub Jelinek from comment #5) > Might as well be just undefined behavior in LLVM/Clang. > Does: > -fno-strict-aliasing -fwrapv -fno-aggressive-loop-optimizations > -fno-lifetime-dse > make a difference?
Will try.
> Can you try -fsanitize=undefined and/or -fsanitize=address ?
Will try.
> If you build with -O0 instead of the default (-O2/-O3 or whatever it uses), > do you still observe issues?
Will try and report back.
> If not, can you bisect which LLVM/Clang *.o > file matters for the test failure?
How would I do that?
Further info, probably useless for practical purpose: does not affect Clang/LLVM 3.9.

(In reply to Vedran Miletić from comment #6) > Will try.
... Thanks.
> > If not, can you bisect which LLVM/Clang *.o > > file matters for the test failure? > > How would I do that? > > Further info, probably useless for practical purpose: does not affect > Clang/LLVM 3.9.
If building with -O0 (or gcc 6) works but with -O2/-O3 doesn't, then do build say with -O2/-O3 (default), cp -a over the build tree somewhere else, do build with -O0 in the same location, cp -a over the build tree somewhere else, and then iteratively replace some *.o files from the -O0 build with corresponding -O2 build (or vice versa), depending on what works and what doesn't. If there is only one problematic *.o file, you'll need log2 (number of *.o files) steps.

I took a quick look at the failure, and my guess is the difference is either in build/tools/clang/lib/Format/CMakeFiles/clangFormat.dir/Format.cpp.o or build/tools/clang/tools/clang-format/CMakeFiles/clang-format.dir/ClangFormat.cpp.o
If that is the case, that is very useful info. Can you try to compile them with -O0 and see if the problem goes away?

(In reply to Jakub Jelinek from comment #9) > If that is the case, that is very useful info. Can you try to compile them > with -O0 and see if the problem goes away?
Problem remains with -O0 and also with fno-strict-aliasing -fwrapv -fno-aggressive-loop-optimizations -fno-lifetime-dse. With -fsanitize=address or -fsanitize=undefined I can't get configure step to pass.
Problem also happens on GCC 7 on Debian, so it's not Fedora specific.

It seems like ClangFormat.cpp.o may be the problem. Here is what I observe:
-O0 CMake Args: -DLLVM_LIBDIR_SUFFIX=64 -DLLVM_TARGETS_TO_BUILD=X86 -DBUILD_SHARED_LIBS=ON -DCMAKE_CXX_FLAGS_DEBUG=-O0 -DLLVM_ABI_BREAKING_CHECKS=FORCE_OFF
-O2 CMake Args: -DLLVM_LIBDIR_SUFFIX=64 -DLLVM_TARGETS_TO_BUILD=X86 -DBUILD_SHARED_LIBS=ON -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release
-O0 Build: Test Passes -O0 Build + -O2 ClangFormat.cpp.o: Test Fails -O2 Build: Test Fails -O2 Build + -O0 ClangFormat.cpp.o: Test Fails
One other thing I noticed is that the test will fail in the -O0 build if I build the LLVM/clang components as static libraries rather than shared libraries. Note that ClangFormat.cpp.o is not part of clang/llvm libraries, it contains the main() function for the clang-format executable.

Which exact test fails? I've built LLVM+clang twice, once with the F25 gcc (6.x), clang-format on disable-include-sorting.cpp looks ok, then rebuilt just ClangFormat.cpp.o + relinked clang-format with 0228-ish gcc trunk, it works the same, then build everything with the 0228-ish gcc trunk (cmake ... -DCMAKE_CXX_COMPILER=... -DCMAKE_C_COMPILER=...), the rest works too, and finally just in case there was something fixed in between 0225 and 0228, tried to rebuild ClangFormat.cpp.o with the 7.0.1-0.10.fc26 cc1plus binary, again, it works the same. So, which test are you looking at and what are the differences?

Ah, seems I've omitted -O2 somewhere. Anyway, if it is a gcc bug, it would be very old, because <b> and then <a> is printed even when the same preprocessed source is compiled with http://gcc.gnu.org/r222000 (close before gcc 5 and various others in between that and now; can't go much older because I'm getting some unresolved symbols then). -O0/-Og "works", -O1 and above doesn't. I have no experience with clang-format, so can somebody debug it side by side, -O0 -g and -O1 -g compiled one and find where things differ?

bool applyAllReplacements(const Replacements &Replaces, Rewriter &Rewrite) @ clang/lib/Tooling/Core/Replacement.cpp:541
The problem with the -O2 build is that the loop in this function executes only once, even though Replaces.size() == 3.

(In reply to Tom Stellard from comment #15) > bool applyAllReplacements(const Replacements &Replaces, Rewriter &Rewrite) @ > clang/lib/Tooling/Core/Replacement.cpp:541 > > The problem with the -O2 build is that the loop in this function executes > only once, even though Replaces.size() == 3.
I still not sure why this happens, but I'm continuing to look into it.

(In reply to Tom Stellard from comment #15) > bool applyAllReplacements(const Replacements &Replaces, Rewriter &Rewrite) @ > clang/lib/Tooling/Core/Replacement.cpp:541 > > The problem with the -O2 build is that the loop in this function executes > only once, even though Replaces.size() == 3.
Note that right now we see different behavior with a different TU depending on -O0/-O2, so if a function in Replacement.cpp.o starts behaving differently, then it must be because of different arguments passed to it, or differences in data structures they point to (or global ones). So in theory it ought to misbehave even when Replacement.cpp.o is compiled with -O0 -g and therefore might be easier to debug

I spent a little more time looking at this, and it looks like the problem is that Replaces.rbegin() points to the first item in the underlying std::set, instead of the last item. Still trying to figure out why this is happening.
Just a quick note that 7.0.1-0.11 from https://koji.fedoraproject.org/koji/buildinfo?buildID=866357 did not accidentally fix this issue. I will keep testing as much as I can.
I observe the same issue when compiling Clang/LLVM 4.0 using Clang 3.9.1 available in Fedora 26 repos. Could it be something other than GCC?

Tom, could you please try to verify the #c21 comment? Perhaps just recompile the single problematic TU with clang. If it doesn't work when built using clang either, it would be a strong hint that it might not be a compiler bug, perhaps it could be a libstdc++ issue (perhaps somebody could try to rebuild it against libc++ to rule that out), or just a clang-format bug. It is still possible both compilers have the same bug, but it isn't very likely.
Maybe also try compiling with -D_GLIBCXX_DEBUG to turn on the libstdc++ iterator debugging checks, which catch a lot of errors. It would be good to rule out a whole class of problems that way.

(In reply to Jakub Jelinek from comment #22) > Tom, could you please try to verify the #c21 comment? Perhaps just > recompile the single problematic TU with clang. > If it doesn't work when built using clang either, it would be a strong hint > that it might not be a compiler bug, perhaps it could be a libstdc++ issue > (perhaps somebody could try to rebuild it against libc++ to rule that out), > or just a clang-format bug. > It is still possible both compilers have the same bug, but it isn't very > likely.
Since it's so neatly packaged in Fedora, trying right now.
(In reply to Jonathan Wakely from comment #23) > Maybe also try compiling with -D_GLIBCXX_DEBUG to turn on the libstdc++ > iterator debugging checks, which catch a lot of errors. It would be good to > rule out a whole class of problems that way.
Will try next.
Clang 4.0 compiled with Fedora-packaged Clang and libc++ 3.9 works fine. What info from -D_GLIBCXX_DEBUG is useful?

(In reply to Vedran Miletić from comment #25) > What info from -D_GLIBCXX_DEBUG is useful?
Does it run normally if you build with that option?

(In reply to Jonathan Wakely from comment #26) > (In reply to Vedran Miletić from comment #25) > > What info from -D_GLIBCXX_DEBUG is useful? > > Does it run normally if you build with that option?
Fails the same way.
OK, it would have aborted with a verbose error message if the _GLIBCXX_DEBUG checks found a problem.
So, what is the next step? Are we sure this issue only affects LLVM?
Maybe this is http://gcc.gnu.org/PR80183 with https://gcc.gnu.org/ml/gcc-patches/2017-03/msg01356.html fix?

(In reply to Jakub Jelinek from comment #30) > Maybe this is http://gcc.gnu.org/PR80183 with > https://gcc.gnu.org/ml/gcc-patches/2017-03/msg01356.html fix?
That does seem to fix it in my testing.
Looks promising, testing.
Yup, all good. Thank you very much. Feel free to mark this as fixed when 7.0.1-0.13 hits the repos.
